Here's the complete migration:

---

### Why it breaks on .NET 8

`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on .NET 6+. `Thread.ResetAbort()` is also gone. The runtime no longer supports preemptive thread termination â€” you **must** use cooperative cancellation.

---

### Migrated code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            var task = Task.Run(work, cts.Token);
            task.Wait(cts.Token);
            return task.Result;
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            throw new AggregateException(ex.InnerException!);
        }
    }
}
```

### If `work` is long-running and must respond to cancellation

Pass the token through so the work can cooperate:

```csharp
public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
    var token = cts.Token;

    try
    {
        var task = Task.Run(() => work(token), token);
        task.Wait(token);
        return task.Result;
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        throw new TimeoutException(
            $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
    catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
    {
        throw new AggregateException(ex.InnerException!);
    }
}

// Caller example:
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(token =>
{
    for (int i = 0; i < 1_000_000; i++)
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // cooperative checkpoint
        DoExpensiveWork(i);
    }
    return computedValue;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

---

### Key pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---------|--------|
| **Cancellation isn't immediate** | Unlike `Thread.Abort`, the token only takes effect at checkpoints. If `work` is a single blocking call (e.g., `Thread.Sleep`, synchronous I/O), it won't stop until it returns. Insert `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` in loops. |
| **Forgetting `using` on CTS** | `CancellationTokenSource` is `IDisposable` â€” leaking it leaks internal timers. Always wrap in `using`. |
| **Swallowing `OperationCanceledException`** | The old code swallowed `ThreadAbortException` via `ResetAbort`. Don't swallow `OperationCanceledException` â€” let it propagate or convert it (as shown: â†’ `TimeoutException`). |
| **Uncooperative work** | If `work` calls code you can't modify (e.g., a blocking native call), cancellation won't interrupt it. The task continues running even after timeout. For truly uncooperative code, move it to a **child process** and use `Process.Kill`. |
| **`Task.Run` uses the thread pool** | The original code created a dedicated thread. If `work` is very long-running, consider `Task.Factory.StartNew` with `TaskCreationOptions.LongRunning` instead of `Task.Run`. |

### What was removed and why

| Old API | Replacement | Reason |
|---------|-------------|--------|
| `thread.Abort()` | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` (via timeout) | `Abort` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` | New exception type for cooperative cancellation |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Removed entirely | No equivalent needed â€” `OperationCanceledException` doesn't auto-rethrow |
